# Script Cleanup & Organization plan

## Goals - long term vision - several iterations
- pay off some technical debt in the form of unwarranted complexity and disorganization of script members and content.
- intoduce clearn architecture like sorting of members
    - Core members: business logic bubble
        - rely only on below layer.utils exclusively 
    - Utils: library support, low level 'work' code 
        - AppProvider static class
            - an range of methods that core-members rely on to do things outside their bubble
        - DefaultPrompt static class
    - Unidirectional flow: core -> utils -> other imports
- file commenting & member sorting
    -sorting
        - shebang
        - 1 fileintro python docstring (""" This script .. """)
        - imports
        - following sections -> seperated by 1 line visually striking python docstring comments:
        - """ STATIC DECLARATIONS """
            - like the comment delimiter string
        - """ CORE MEMBERS """ (sorted by importance)
            - like harness & others
            - forbidden to rely externally on anything other than utils layer code.
        - """ UTILS """
            - new static class to provide all required external functionality of above. 
            - absorbs low level code from core which would otherwise infer external dependencies there.
    - member comments
        - static declarations -> no comments
        - all classes get 1 python docstring line-comment each (just on the inside of def, like we do in pythn)
            - then each of their methods similarly get a ds line-comment
        - no other comments are allowed:
            - inline 'explainer comments'


## New core member lineup. 
# - User is served by nested implementations of class Manager. Managers run a loop, to offer the user a view, and bind letters to functionality they offer the user, or to forwards to other managers, in a downstream fashion.
# - Other core members may be services, which support the managers.
#       - for example, DataService provide all managers with tailored persistence and data methods

long term vision:

        class Harness: Seems to doing app init, display and business logic. we split it up
            def get_char(self):
            def load_config_from_disk(self):
            def start(self):
            def handle(self, command):
            def render(self):

                -> new function main, unattached to any class.
                    - called by __main__  on app (__main__ is at very bottom of utils)
                    - main function location is very top of core. 
                    - it initializes all services, and the commandmanager, passing him all services (there is but one at the moment)
                    - it does CommandManager.start() in a try catch loop. we use this to ensure all uncaught errors find their way to the console in proper verbose fashion.
                        - so rest of code can take the fail fast, sending anything they dont explicitly catch themselves back to main for centralized visibility.
                            - error handling in other core members should be part of the business logic. ideally we dont declare the exceptions, but perhaps have a exceptions enum or dict to represent the exceptions.
                            - errors that bubble to main cause verbose loggin, then exit 1. no survival from that point on.
                -> new static class ConsoleViews, to contain render() type methods for manager type classes
                -> new class CommandManager. handles letter commands, be they prompts or forward routing to other managers.
                -> new class Manager (Standard ABC ?). for other managers to inherit. inheritors can then use their init to set up the loop:
                        self.loop.setRenderFunc(ConsoleViews.the-view) (the render function is a 1. class func arg) return self (fluid style)
                        self.loop.setCmd(letter, cmd_text, self.designated_handler_method, optional_confirm_text) return self (fluid style)

        class EnvironmentManager. we split it up
